PiperOrigin-RevId: 621349766

Improved Interfaces for Swift

Added a new annotation named `@SwiftName` and has one argument for the name. It will be available for package, class/interface, and methods. Also added a build flag named `--swift-naming` and it has the same effect as the annotation.

When the annotation is added on the package it use the java name as the swift name for all classes and methods. When added on a class or method level, it will allow renaming of that class or method for Swift. If no argument is added it use the Java name.

Currently enums make a NS_ENUM and Class type. The annotation will fold the class type into the enum type in Swift. There is also two new methods for converting between the types.

PiperOrigin-RevId: 621310553

Replaces use of `mac_absolute_time()` with `clock_gettime_nsec_np(CLOCK_MONOTONIC)` in `java.lang.System.nanoTime()` implementation. The returned value is no longer relatable to other system times, instead only useful for measuring elapsed time (as the method's javadoc describes).

I have omitted some values that I'm hoping we don't need (e.g., scm tag, developer timeZone and roles like [we have in Guava](https://github.com/google/guava/blob/0b1c477311b2c7a0a89f5e0ac785084e3ab15d34/pom.xml#L59)). (I am morally opposed in particular to expressing a time zone as an offset of hours from UTC, at least without setting up a reminder to update it for every DST transition :) OK, it looks like [we can actually use a real zone](https://maven.apache.org/pom.html#developers) if we need one.)

commit.message:
Migrate from deprecated boxed primitive constructors to their replacements. E.g., `new Integer(...)` becomes `Integer.valueOf(...)`.

The boxed primitive constructors are deprecated **for removal**. That means these APIs _will be deleted_ in a future JDK release and this library _will stop compiling_!

NOTE: if piper is _not_ the source of truth for this 3p library, please work with upstream maintainers to land this change (it is your responsibility to do so --- see "Review & accept maintenance changes" @ go/thirdparty/responsibilities#owner).

More info: go/boxed-primitive-constructors-lsc b/321209431

PiperOrigin-RevId: 602195635

Simplest fix for unsafe put/getObject used with volatile fields. Make
all accesses use the volatile functions. This is always correct for
volatile fields and eliminates any memory ordering assumptions for
get/putObject for unsafe operations.

Mixing put/getObject with normal field access for non-volatile fields
would now use volatile locks on the unsafe path, which is unnecessary
but harmless. Compiling with experimental "strict field" options for
non-volatile fields will now interop with unsafe correctly.
